```python
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Sample data
years = [2010, 2012, 2018]
sectors = ['Al', 'CS']
investment = [
    [3.5, 4.5, 5.5],
    [2.5, 3.5, 4.5]
]

# Create a new figure
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10.0, 8.0))

# Plot the first subplot
ax1 = fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)
for i, sector in enumerate(sectors):
    ax1.bar(years, investment[i], label=sector)
ax1.set_xlabel('Year')
ax1.set_ylabel('Investment (Billion USD)')
ax1.set_title('Investment by Year and Sector')
ax1.legend()

# Plot the second subplot
ax2 = fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)
time_since_intro = np.arange(10)
tech_level = np.arange(10)
data = np.random.rand(10, 10)
cax = ax2.pcolormesh(time_since_intro, tech_level, data, shading='auto')
fig.colorbar(cax, ax=ax2)
ax2.set_xlabel('Time Since Introduction (Years)')
ax2.set_ylabel('Technology Level')
ax2.set_title('Adoption Rate')

# Show the plot
plt.show()
```

}

axes[0, 0].set_xscale('log')

# Plot the second graph
axes[0, 1].plot(N, precision_1.T, label='Precision')
axes[0, 1].set_xscale('log')
axes[0, 1].set_title('Graph Variation 1')

# Plot the third graph
axes[1, 0].plot(N, peak_performance_1.T, label='Peak Performance')
axes[1, 0].set_xscale('log')
axes[1, 0].set_title('Graph Variation 3')
axes[1, 0].legend()

plt.ylabel('Delta Value')

plt.title('Cumulative Sum Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Time')
plt.ylabel('Cumulative Value')
